    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 14th with a diverse lineup, anchored by **Yordan Alvarez** (72.47), whose matchup against Lorenzen presents our highest ceiling of the day. Despite a slight park penalty, **Yordan Alvarez** benefits significantly from a favorable order placement and a high xwOBA profile. While **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (63.51) sits lower in the order, his dynamic platoon advantage against Nola provides a strong scoring boost, making him a sneaky high-floor play despite the suppression caused by the catcher's arm and high stolen-base-prevention metrics. Conversely, we must exercise caution with **Trea Turner** (59.08) and **Kyle Schwarber** (57.26); their base projections are solid, but they are running into a buzzsaw in opposing starter Martin, whose 0.00 xERA suggests a dominant, albeit likely short-stint, outing that severely suppresses their overall efficiency.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Victor Scott II** (39.65), who missed our 40.0 scoring floor by the slimmest of margins. While **Victor Scott II** is a critical asset for our scarcity-driven stolen base strategy, the combination of a poor batting order spot and a lack of a platoon advantage against Cantillo forced a defensive benching to preserve our game caps. Elsewhere, we continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich** and **Colt Keith**, both of whom remain unavailable, and **Zac Veen**, who is currently working to earn a call-up from Albuquerque. With the bottom of our order featuring **Carson Benge** (42.30) and **Hyeseong Kim** (43.91) facing elite-tier arms in Yamamoto and McLean respectively, we are betting on the top-heavy production from **Junior Caminero** (61.03) and **Caleb Durbin** (61.94) to carry the day\u2019s offensive output. Any late lineup shifts regarding **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Josh Smith**, or **Luis Pena** will be scrutinized, but for now, the roster remains set to maximize our 5x5 potential while respecting the strict game-cap floor.",
